The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Tuesday, August 31, 2004  The City Diary
																																																		Doctors with Master in Surgery (MS) and Doctor of Medicine (MD) degrees will be allowed to study diploma courses in healthcare. Health minister Surjya Kanta Mishra announced this at a conference on healthcare, organised by the Bengal National Chamber of Commerce and Industry, on Monday. The Medical Council of India , he said, has lifted the bar on pursuing diploma courses after getting a masters degree. Mishra announced the government will increase its aid to clinics, provided they kept a few beds reserved for the poor. 																																																		Promoter Pradip Kundalia, arrested in connection with a fire in a building constructed by him on Shakespeare Sarani, was remanded in jail custody till September 13. 																																																		Criminal Gudda, an associate of Gabbar, was sentenced to three years rigorous imprisonment by the city civil court on Monday. He was arrested for injuring the officer-in-charge of Beniapukur police station in 1996 and for his involvement in a number of dacoity and murder cases. 																																																		The Publishers and Booksellers Guild held its 28th annual general meeting on Monday to elect office-bearers and executive committee members. Kalyan Shah was elected president and Tridib Kumar Chatterjee honorary general secretary. 																																																		Residents of Thakurpukur blocked Diamond Harbour Road for two hours on Monday morning. They were demanding the arrest of a criminal who had assaulted the brother of a local trader. To the Traffic Police and People For Animals for a joint drive to rid congested city roads of stray bulls and rehabilitate them
